Aquilio: Μ’. Aquilius was sent out <89 Rc.) as conimissioner to restore the kings of Bithynia and Cappadocia, whom Mithridates had expelled. Mithridates yielded without opposition, but Aquilius, disappointed in his hopes of plunder, instigated the restored monarehs to acts of aggression against Pontus, thus precipitating the first Mithridatio war (88 B.C.). Mithridates, after he had captured Aquilius, is said to have poured molten gold down his throat, to mark that his avarice had been the cause cf all the ensuing calamities (App. Mithrid. 7. 19. 21 ; Pliny, N.H. 33. 3. 48). Cf. Arnob. Adv. Nat. 1. 40.
